description:
Course content is based on a family centered approach in which the needs of the family members during various phases of the childbearing process are considered. The student is provided with a theory base necessary for the care of women, families, and their newborns. This theory base is organized according to the concepts of the person or family, environment, health and nursing and their relation to each other during childbearing. Using the nursing process, nursing strategies are developed for maintaining family members individually, for promoting optimal physiological and psychological functioning, and enhancing strengths within the family members and within the family unit. 

Clinical experiences provide opportunities for application and integration of the theory base with parents and newborns. The student participates in clinical experiences in a variety of settings including acute care facilities, the community, and the Instructional Technology Center (ITC). The student will care for families with both simple and complex needs in all phases of the childbearing cycle. During this course, the student will assist in managing the care of families during the antepartum, intrapartum, postpartum, and neonatal periods.

values.comments:
Nursing 210 bases its content on a family centered approach in which the needs of the family members during various phases of the childbearing process are considered. The student is provided with a theory base necessary for the care of women, families, and their newborns. This theory base is organized according to the concepts of the person or family, environment, health and nursing and their relation to each other during childbearing. Using the nursing process, nursing strategies are developed for maintaining family members individually, for promoting optimal physiological and psychological functioning, and enhancing strengths within the family members and within the family unit.

Some students remarked that they would like “a little more structure to the lectures.” On the other hand, others felt that “instructors, pace, and information [were] impeccable.” Students generally thought that most of the grade “should come from the lab” since that was the largest time commitment. Additionally, many felt that the paper did not seem to contribute to much of the learning in the class; one student even recommended that it be “extended to 7 pages.” Overall, the course seemed to be “enjoyable.” 

Though there were no comments specific to Professor Stern, students seemed to agree that the professors should have synchronized calendars. One student emphasized that it was “difficult to distinguish which instructor was in charge of what,” and another student commented that there was “a lot of variation among individual instructors.”

Many students felt that it was often hard to sit through the three-hour lecture, which could be very “boring.” The grade distribution “was not reflective…of the amount of time and effort required for certain assignments.” One student suggested that having “group exams or post-test review would” have been helpful.

Nursing 210 is based on a family centered approach in which the needs of the family members during various phases of the childbearing process are considered. The student is provided with a theory base necessary for the care of women, families, and their newborns. This theory base is organized according to the concepts of the person or family, environment, health and nursing and their relation to each other during childbearing. Using the nursing process, nursing strategies are developed for maintaining family members individually, for promoting optimal physiological and psychological functioning, and enhancing strengths within the family members and within the family unit. Clinical experiences provide opportunities for application and integration of the theory base with parents and newborns. The student participates in clinical experiences in a variety of settings including acute care facilities, the community, and the Instructional Technology Center (ITC). The student will care for families with both simple and complex needs in all phases of the childbearing cycle. During this course, the student will assist in managing the care of families during the antepartum, intrapartum, postpartum, and neonatal periods.

The primary complaint about this course was that it was “confusing,” “poorly organized,” and “inconsistent.” Many students consequently felt as though the information they were leaning was not properly utilized and reinforced, and that the class was “not conducive to learning.” However, some students found the class to be “very informative” and thought that the “lab was very interactive.” Overall, students seemed to feel that “the material could be presented much better” and that “the labs,” in particular, were “a waste of time.”

Students generally felt that communication in the classroom was “inefficient” and “could be improved.” Many complained that there were “inconsistencies” and that “there are a bunch of different instructors teaching different techniques.” Several also felt there was not sufficient support provided during open lab hours. However, some students felt that Professor Ioranni-Cimbak was “very open to constructive comments” and that the lab continually improved with student feedback. 

Many students reported that the workload per week was too heavy and was not reflected in the exams. Several students complained that the information tested was provided “informally,” and that, due to the fact that instructors were frequently “unclear on what was expected,” “the examinations for this class are not designed for [students] to pass them, but rather for us to somehow manage to not fail them.” One student attested that he spent 12 hours on each “module,” and several commented that they “take an immense amount of time” and “feel like busy work.” Some students, though, were pleased that correct answers were provided and reviewed after turning in the assignment.
